It also comes with the best charging handle on the market, the Rainier Arms Raptor ambidextrous charging handle, also comes with a standard M4 charging handle. Also comes with 5 PMAGS. The rifle alone I am selling for $1500, bought it at jimmy's in fwb two weeks ago for $1856, you can go there and check the prices. I also have a ton of ammo and gear to go along with it. I also have 1300 rounds of 5.56 ammunition, 750 of which is 55grain winchester whitebox/independence/pmc xtac/zq1, and 550 rounds are 5.56 62 grain green tipped armor piercing rounds. I am asking 520 for all the ammo, thats only .40 cents per round, cheaper than walmart. I also have 2 rifle cases, a bore snake, two bottles of CLP, a Grip/Bipod, and a Magpul BAD lever. For everything I will let it go for $2,000. For rifle alone $1500, for ammo alone $520. If interested send me a message on here, or call/text me at 850 585 1393. can text any time day or night.

The SureFire high-capacity magazine for 5.56x45 mm (.223 Remington) ammunition, is compatible with M4/M16/AR-15 variants and other firearms that accept standard STANAG 4179 magazines. Constructed from Mil-Spec hard-anodized aluminum, they feed smoothly and reliably due to optimal geometry, non-binding coil springs, and ingenious nesting polymer followers. The long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance. Magazines require no lubricants and can be easily disassembled without tools for cleaning.

SureFire High-Capacity magazines provide distinct tactical advantages: increased initial firepower in ambush situations; fewer reloads overall, which means less downtime and target distraction in a firefight; fast and easy magazine insertion, even with a closed bolt; less bulk compared to drum mags, enabling a normal weapon grip. The 60-round magazine—slightly thinner than two 30-round magazines clipped together and about the same overall length—fits in most dual magazine pouches, eliminating special carry pouches required for drum magazines. May be kept fully loaded for extended periods without spring fatigue.

40,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3166040,"For Sale:  Glock 26, Gen 3, Nickel Boron coated!!! Like new!","Murfreesboro, Nashville, Tennessee",$ 535,"Listed On: Thursday, June 12, 2014",Handguns,Glock                                                                                ,9mm Luger (9x19)                                                                                ,Striker Fire                                                                                ,Pistol,"Up for sale is my generation 3 Glock 26. This pistol has the nickel Boron coating over Glocks standard tennifer on the slide, internals, and barrel. In case you are unfamiliar with nickel Boron, it is an ion bonding process that results in a finish that is like stainless steel in appearance, however, it has a lifetime warranty to NEVER chip, crack, or rust. This stuff is near indestructible. I have seen torture test that are unbelievable. People have left guns with this coating in Salt water for 12 months without a single spot of corrosion. They also say you don't have to ever clean or lubricate the gun because the nickel boron has high lubricity. All you ever do is give it a quick wipe and pass a patch down the barrel. However, having said that, this gun has been cleaned regularly anyway.

This pistol is in like new condition. I bought it new and have put maybe 75 rounds through it. I'm only selling to make room for a new purchase. The pistol comes in the original box, with two magazines. One of the magazines has a finger grip extender that makes drawing and firing much easier. The grip has a rubberized talon decal to help with the grip, but if you don't like it you can remove it. Also comes with the factory speed loader and a nice leather in the waistband holster from Tagua. Let me know if you have any questions, and thanks for looking!"

46,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3166046,For Sale:  Sig Sauer P320,"niles, Youngstown, Ohio",$ 590,"Listed On: Thursday, July 10, 2014",Handguns,Sig Sauer                                                                                ,9mm Luger (9x19)                                                                                ,Striker Fire                                                                                ,Pistol,"The P320 is a polymer-framed service pistol designed from the ground up with the input of law enforcement officers. The result is the most operator-safety focused striker duty pistol on the market today. Taking into account the concerns of military and police training officers, the P320 provides an enhanced level of safety not found on most modern service pistols. Unlike its competitors, the P320 does not require the operator to pull the trigger nor use a special tool to take-down the firearm for cleaning or routine maintenance. Featuring a modular grip frame and removable fire control assembly pioneered by Sig Sauer, the P320 is customizable to any hand size or duty requirement. The P320 can quickly be converted from a Full-size to a Carry pistol. Slide and barrel conversions allow the P320 to change between calibers and barrel lengths as well. The P320 will be immediately available in 9mm, .40S&W and .357SIG, with .45ACP coming later in 2014. With a partially pretensioned striker, the P320 has a short, crisp trigger pull with a quick, pronounced reset right out-of-the-box. Featuring the Sig internal safety system, the P320 has no external safety or decocking lever to snag or hang up on the draw. SigLite night sights come standard, and the reversible magazine release makes the P320 completely ambidextrous. For more information please feel free to contact me at REDACTED. 222,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3166222,"For Sale:  Converted Saiga 12 - Nice - $1,900","Meadville, Meadville / Grove City, Pennsylvania","$ 1,900","Listed On: Thursday, July 3, 2014",Shotguns,Saiga                                                                                ,12 Gauge                                                                                ,Semi-automatic                                                                                ,Shotgun,"I'm listing my favorite for sale as it's time for a down payment on a house, that's the only reason. There's nothing wrong with it. I purchased it in 2011 when they were scarce and converted it with the help of my machinist father. The conversion was done to exceed that required by the BATF 922, not just to make it look awesome. Be careful what you buy because not all 'conversions' are equal... some are illegal. This one has an ACE (long) skeleton stock, with a folding mechanism and folding drum adapter so the stock can lock in position with the drum installed. All it needs to dump the mag in that position - from the hip- is a different spring to compensate for the lack of shoulder. From the shoulder it fires whatever will fit with the help of an MD arms gas puck and improved regulator plug. The front site ball was removed and replaced with a threaded in set screw (with the spike point up) when I drilled out the 4 gas ports.. from the factory 2 were partially closed, one was obscured and it wouldn't fire low-brass. No problems now. The fire control group and trigger guard has been relocated and replaced, the pistol grip is CAA with the adjustable fit for your hand. The fore-grip is a SGM tri-rail with a removable folding vertical grip installed. This comes with an MD Arms 20rd drum, pro mag 10 round stick, and the stock 5 round stick mag. Also a single point sling that attaches to the folding stock mechanism. This has been fired and enjoyed... so I know it works. If you want to buy it bring a box of shells and it'll eat them up. I'm not interested in taking less so don't ask. Sale will be cash in hand in person, bring PA identification. NO SHIPPING."

751,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3166751,For Sale:  Intratec TEC DC-9,"USF, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida",$ 600,"Listed On: Friday, August 22, 2014",Handguns,Intratec                                                                                ,9mm Luger (9x19)                                                                                ,Single Action                                                                                ,Pistol,"Tec-9
9mm pistol

FOUR 32RD magazines (3 are factory originals)
trade for AK Pistol, 1911 TYPE PISTOL

The Intratec TEC DC-9 ""assault pistol"", also known as DC-9, TEC-9, or, if manufactured after 1994, as AB-10, bears the dubious distinction of being one of the most widely used ""criminal"" guns in USA. It was used in several mass murder cases, as well as in unknown, but definitely large number of street fights and other violent crimes. TEC-9 became ""famous"" for its ""evil"" appearance, large magazine capacity (which offered significant firepower), and for low price. Unsurprisingly, these features made TEC-9 very popular among various marginal types. For any serious or professional shooter this gun vas of little value - it was too big and heavy to be carried comfortably, it was too unreliable when firing anything but FMJ ammunition, and the accuracy with very crude fixed sights was about marginal.

The TEC-9 design was started in Sweden, when the Interdynamic AB company of Stockholm developed a relatively simple submachine gun. Since Sweden was a poor market for such product, a subsidiary company Interdynamic was established in Miami (Florida, USA), to market Interdynamic guns in USA. As the full-automatic weapons market in USA is very restrictive, the basic submachine gun was converted in semi-automatic only variant, apparently suitable for civilian US market. This semi-automatic pistol, like its submachine gun predecessor, was a simple blowback design, firing from the open bolt. It was designated Interdynamic KG-9. But, sooner than later, US Bureau of  Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (BATF) found that this semiautomatic pistol can be easily converted back to full automatic, and restricted it manufacture. Interdynamic redesigned the KG-9 into ""closed bolt"" design by adding the separate striker, and designated it KG-99. About the same time (mid-1980s) the Interdynamic of USA turned into Intratec Firearms, Inc, based in the same city of Miami (Florida). Intratec initially  produced the KG-99 under the designation of  TEC-9, but about 1989 renamed it into DC-9. With the introduction of the infamous US Assault Weapons Ban in 1994 the Intratec pistols were prohibited for manufacture (but not for ownership, if made before the ban). Intratec subsequently slightly redesigned the basic design, dropping some ""assault"" features like the threaded barrel, barrel shroud, and forward pistol grip. In this ""post-ban"" version the pistol was manufactured and sold as AB-10 (AB stands for After Ban). The AB-10 pistols were sold with 10-round magazines, but still could accept both factory and aftermarket high capacity magazines from its predecessors, TEC-9 and DC-9. There were several manufacturers in US, who made copies of DC-9, such as AA Arms, which produced DC-9 look-alike AP-9 pistols. Like originals, AP-9 pistols were of cheap construction and marginal reliability.

The Interdynamics and Intratec pistols are blowback operated, semi-automatic weapons. The major difference between Interdynamic KG-9 and Intratec TEC-9/AB-10 line of pistols is that KG-9 fired from the open bolt, and had a fixed firing pin; the Intratec pistols fire from closed bolt, and have a separate firing pin and a massive striker, which interoperates with the sear. The receivers of all versions are made from steel tube (either carbon or stainless), the frames (or ""lower receivers"") are made from polymer, integral with pistol grip and magazine housing ahead of the trigger guard. The tubular receiver is hinged to the front of the frame. There is no manual safety. The open-bolt Interdynamic KG-9 pistols featured a special cut, in which the charging handle can be locked when bolt in retracted. The KG-99 and Interdynamic pistols have manual safety built into charging handle - to lock the bolt, one must push the charging handle inward. All pistols are fed from double stack, detachable box magazines; standard magazine capacity was 20 or 32 rounds for pre-ban guns, and 10 rounds for post-ban guns. After-market magazines were offered in various capacities up to 50 rounds. Permanently fixed open sights were not adjustable, and often misaligned. In the pre-ban TEC-9 and DC-9 versions these pistol accepted screw-on barrel extensions, which had purely cosmetic purposes, or silencers (which were illegal in many jurisdictions)."
